# Centering a Div

There are several ways to center a div depending on your needs. Here are the most common methods:

## 1. Flexbox (Most Common & Recommended)

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center; /* horizontal */
  align-items: center;     /* vertical */
  height: 100vh;           /* needs height for vertical centering */
}
```

## 2. Grid (Cleanest for both axes)

```css
.parent {
  display: grid;
  place-items: center;
  height: 100vh;
}
```

## 3. Absolute Positioning + Transform

```css
.parent {
  position: relative;
}

.child {
  position: absolute;
  top: 50%;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);
}
```

## 4. Horizontal Centering Only (margin auto)

```css
.child {
  width: 300px;        /* must have a defined width */
  margin: 0 auto;
}
```

## Quick Reference

| Method | Best For |
|--------|----------|
| **Flexbox** | Most situations, especially aligning content |
| **Grid** | Quick centering of single items |
| **Absolute + Transform** | Centering over other content / overlays |
| **margin: auto** | Simple horizontal centering of block elements |

## Example: Complete Flexbox Solution

```html
<div class="parent">
  <div class="child">I'm centered!</div>
</div>
```

```css
.parent {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  min-height: 100vh;
}
```

**My recommendation:** Use **Flexbox** for most cases — it's reliable, readable, and well-supported.

